post_text:
USD 320 Wamego is accepting applications for Certified Nurse’s Aides. Applicants must hold, at minimum, a CNA license. Hours may vary based on need, but will be approximately 7:15am - 3:45pm with a 30 minute lunch break.

Knowledge of current Microsoft Office programs, including Word and Excel is preferred. Good communication skills (both verbal and written) and good phone skills are essential. The ability to multi-task is a must.

Duties may include screening staff and students prior to entry into school buildings, caring for ill students throughout the school day, administering medications, assisting school nurses with documentation, and other duties as assigned.

This position will be a KPERS retirement covered position, and will be eligible for a medical and supplemental insurance package.

Applicants must apply online at https://wamego.tedk12.com/hire

If you have any questions about the application process please contact Kati Wolfgang at wolfgangk@usd320.com or 785-456-7643.

shared_text:
K-State College of Education
May 18 at 10:35 AM ·

On March 17, 2020, schools across Kansas closed for the safety of their students and communities because of the COVID-19 pandemic. School districts were given approximately one week to formulate plans to remote teach for the remainder of the school year. This is the story of how one rural school district in Kansas met those needs.

At Kansas State University, we were inspired by Wamego USD 320's service, adaptability and commitment. While they would be the first to admit it was not all perfect, we found their courage, strength and compassion remarkable, and we know there are many more stories like it throughout the state.

We'd also like to acknowledge the phenomenal leadership at the Kansas State Department of Education and several of the Kansas Teachers of the Year whose work created a model for remote teaching used by Wamego schools.

Please share this with anyone -- in education or not -- who'd appreciate this story.
text:
K-State College of Education
May 18 at 10:35 AM ·

On March 17, 2020, schools across Kansas closed for the safety of their students and communities because of the COVID-19 pandemic. School districts were given approximately one week to formulate plans to remote teach for the remainder of the school year. This is the story of how one rural school district in Kansas met those needs.

At Kansas State University, we were inspired by Wamego USD 320's service, adaptability and commitment. While they would be the first to admit it was not all perfect, we found their courage, strength and compassion remarkable, and we know there are many more stories like it throughout the state.

We'd also like to acknowledge the phenomenal leadership at the Kansas State Department of Education and several of the Kansas Teachers of the Year whose work created a model for remote teaching used by Wamego schools.

Please share this with anyone -- in education or not -- who'd appreciate this story.

post_text: In response to parent feedback from our Continuous Learning Plan survey, we had a STEM club for all West Elementary families that wanted to participate. Siblings could participate in teams, working on the project together and using one Zoom meeting account. We met on Mondays for an hour. The challenge was given at 1:00pm via Zoom. Students were then given 5 minutes to create an illustration of their challenge idea and ask clarifying questions. Students were then broken into smaller groups with an adult (depending on the size of our STEM Club) and allowed time to build and test their idea. Students could ask their group for suggestions or help while building and made adjustments to their invention during this time. Each student had the opportunity to share their invention at the end.

Hi Parents,
Welcome to the first day of USD 320's Continuous Learning Plan, we hope that all is going well.
If your student is having trouble connecting to any of our services, please follow the steps below:

1. Use the link below as a guide for troubleshooting
https://sites.google.com/usd320.com/techhelp/home

2. You may also contact your teacher, as they are the first point of contact for troubleshooting tech issues.

3. If you have tried these, and you are still experiencing difficulty you may e-mail helpdesk@usd320.com

Keep in mind that applications like google classroom, seesaw, and other educational services are being heavily used and we may see performance issues. Most issues that have been reported are a slowdown in downloads from seesaw.

The majority of issues we are seeing, are regarding the school owned device not authenticating to our proxy. Please use the site for troubleshooting these issues.

https://sites.google.com/usd320.com/techhelp/home

post_text:
KINDERGARTEN ROUND-UP!

It’s time for Central Elementary School’s Kindergarten Round-Up for the 2020-2021 school year! Children must be five on or before Aug. 31, 2020 to attend kindergarten. There is an Open House and an important Parent Mtg. scheduled for Thursday, April 2nd from 6-7:00pm. There is a large possibility that this meeting will be rescheduled for a later time! Please get pre-registered so you are kept up to date!
**Please pre-register your child online at the USD320 website Enrollment tab - Online Registration - 2020-2021 New Kindergarten Pre-Registration. This pre-registration is to gather important contact information. You will still need to do online enrollment in July when it is available. We need this pre-registration information in order to keep you updated on changes. Thank you!!
Please call the office at 785-456-7271 if you have questions and spread the word if you know any children in the community who will be 5 years old before August 31st!

Thank you for being patient with us while we work to handle this unprecedented situation involving COVID-19.

Per the decision of the USD 320 Board of Education Wamego schools will be closed the week of March 16-20, 2020. All classes, activities, and athletics will not be held.

We know this situation brings many questions. We will try to get information out in a timely manner about how we will proceed.

post_text: Ms. Lisa Roberts Proffitt with Flagshipkansas.tech and Ms. Southwest 2020 Sierra Bonn made a brief presentation and talk about STEAM to Mrs. Jardine's Game Design students and 6th hour Computer Applications students. Three of Mrs. Jardine's Game Design students participated at the December State Board of Education meeting in Topeka, and then again to the USD 320 Board of Education on Monday night. For their efforts the class received a Evo Robot by Ozobot.edu. It will be used to further computer coding at the Wamego Middle School. Pictured left to right are: Mrs. Jardine, Lisa Roberts Proffitt, Ryan Holloway, Zy Frizzell, Gabi Herren, Gemma Hovind and Sierra Bonn.
